2 NEW SECTION. Section 2. Requirement to verify all new employees. (1) (a) Except as provided
3 in subsection (2), an employer shall:
4 (i) register and create an e-verify employer account;
5 (ii) after hiring a new employee, submit the employee's name and information for employment
6 verification, even if the employment is terminated less than 3 business days after it began; and
7 (iii) keep a record of the verified work authorization for the duration of the new employee's
8 employment or for 3 years, whichever is longer.
9 (b) (i) A new employee's employment is considered provisional until the employee's work
10 authorization has been verified as provided in subsection (1)(a)(ii).
11 (ii) If a new employee's work authorization is not verified as provided in subsection (1)(a)(ii), a
12 private employer may not employ, continue to employ, or reemploy the new employee.
13 (2) An employer is not required to comply with subsection (1) if:
14 (a) an employee was hired by the employer prior to October 1, 2025;
15 (b) the employer is not required to verify the employee's eligibility to work pursuant to federal law.
16
17 NEW SECTION. Section 3. Compliance with federal immigration law. Nothing in [sections 1
18 through 9] abrogates an employer's obligation to comply with federal immigration laws, including the completion
19 and maintenance of federal employment eligibility verification forms or documents.
20
21 NEW SECTION. Section 4. Employment of unauthorized workers. An employer may not employ
22 an unauthorized worker. Failure to comply with requirements in [sections 2 or 3] are violations of this section.
23
